A dovetail joint is a woodworking joint used to connect two pieces of wood, most commonly in drawer construction.

The joint consists of wedge-shaped pins and tails that interlock mechanically. This structure prevents the joint from being pulled apart and provides high strength without relying only on glue or fasteners.

Dovetail joints have been used in cabinetmaking for centuries and remain one of the most recognizable elements of traditional furniture making.
